Maximum heart rate is the maximum heart: Maximum heart rate is the maximum heart rate measured during the exercise test. The value is not the maximum that the heart can handle but is determined by the cooperation between lungs, heart and muscles. The value depends on the structure of the exercise test and which sport is being practiced. With a running test the maximum heart rate is higher than with a bicycle test. In this case, the course of heart rate and power is determined with a bicycle test. For the heart this is a submaximal exercise test.

The time between consecutive heart beats: The time between consecutive heart beats varies, this is known as Heart Rate Variability (HRV). HRV gives important information about the functioning of the autonomic nervous system. Research shows that a high HRV is related to a higher level of fitness and relaxation, while a low HRV is related to fatigue and stress.
